<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="2154aae5-903c-5856-94a0-6feb4cfefa0b" activityNameId="3912f4fa-fc23-526b-8eee-034b7102a576" parentActivityId="928c51d2-0ac4-544c-b8af-c01641270a80" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">triphenyl phosphate production</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Phosphoric acid, triphenyl ester</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Triphenoxyphosphine oxide</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Disflamoll TP</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Triphenylphosphate</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Triphenyl phosphate production is the result of the reaction of phosphorus oxychloride and phenol. The final product is usually either in flakes or in liquid form, it is transported in jacketed vessel ensuring continuous heating (Brooke et al. 2009).The global production volume in 2000 of triphenyl phosphate was estimated to be between 20 and 30 thousand tonnes; the entire production was supplied by 15 companies (OECD 2002). 90% of this product is used as a flame retardant for different products: 50% for PVC production; 22% polymers (non PVC); 11% printed circuit boards; 7% photographic films (OECD 2002).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Brooke, D. N. et al. 2009. Using science to create a better place: Environmental risk evaluation report: Triphenyl phosphate (CAS no. 115-86-6). Environment Agency</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">OECD. 2002. SIDS Initial Assessment Report For SIAM 15. TRIPHENYL PHOSPHATE CAS N°: 115-86-6. UNEP PUBLICATIONS</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">For more information on the model please refer to the dedicate ecoinvent report, access it in the Report section of ecoQuery (http://www.ecoinvent.org/login-databases.html)</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="34dbbff8-88ce-11de-ad60-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">GLO</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inputs to the process are calculated based on stoichiometry and literature data, they are therefore considered to be valid for the chosen geography. The inputs of heat, electricity, water, factory and nitrogen are mostly taken as average of industry data. Industry data values are a 5-year average of data (2011 - 2015) published by the Gendorf factory (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2015, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2014, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de). The Gendorf factory is based in Germany, it produces a wide range of chemical substances. The factory produced 1657400 tonnes of chemical substances in the year 2015 (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de) and 740000 tonnes of intermediate products. Given the range of chemicals produced by the german site, the values are used for the GLO geography, with uncertainty adjusted accordingly.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Triphenyl phosphate is the result of the reaction of phosphorus oxychloride and phenol (Brooke et al. 2009). In the process 3 moles of hydrogen chloride are produced per mole of reference product.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Hydrochloric acid is produced in the reaction. Hydrochloric acid is neutralized with sodium hydroxide resulting in emissions of sodium chloride.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Chemical reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">POCl3 + 3 HOC6H5 -&gt; OP(OC6H5)3 + 3 HCl</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">This inventory representing production of a particular chemical compound is at least partially based on a generic model on the production of chemicals. The data generated by this model have been improved by compound-specific data when available.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">The model on production of chemicals is using specific industry or literature data wherever possible and more generic data on chemical production processes to fill compound-specific data gaps when necessary. The basic principles of the model have been published in literature (Hischier 2005, Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability). The model has been updated and extended with newly available data from the chemical industry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">In the model, unreacted fractions are treated in a waste treatment process, and emissions reported are after a waste treatment process that is included in the scope of this dataset. For volatile reactants, a small level of evaporation is assumed. Solvents and catalysts are mostly recycled in closed-loop systems within the scope of the dataset and reported flows are for losses from this system.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">The main source of information for the values for heat, electricity, water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from Gendorf. The values are a 5-year average of data (2011 - 2015) published by the Gendorf factory (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2015, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2014, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de). The Gendorf factory is based in Germany, it produces a wide range of chemical substances. The factory produced 1657400 tonnes of chemical substances in the year 2015 (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de) and 740000 tonnes of intermediate products.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59–67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Brooke, D. N. et al. 2009. Using science to create a better place: Environmental risk evaluation report: Triphenyl phosphate (CAS no. 115-86-6). Environment Agency</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="12">OECD. 2002. SIDS Initial Assessment Report For SIAM 15. TRIPHENYL PHOSPHATE CAS N°: 115-86-6. UNEP PUBLICATIONS</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="13">For more information on the model please refer to the dedicate ecoinvent report, access it in the Report section of ecoQuery (http://www.ecoinvent.org/login-databases.html)</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2015-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The activity is based on stoichiometry and literature data, it is therefore considered not to change significantly over time in terms of inputs.  The inputs of heat, electricity, water, factory and nitrogen are mostly taken as average of industry data. Industry data values are a 5-year average of data (2011 - 2015) published by the Gendorf factory (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2015, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de), (Gendorf, 2014, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de). The Gendorf factory is based in Germany, it produces a wide range of chemical substances. The factory produced 1657400 tonnes of chemical substances in the year 2015 (Gendorf, 2016, Umwelterklärung, www.gendorf.de) and 740000 tonnes of intermediate products. The time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="51bb36ba-0332-528e-bfbf-4ad4382be8d7" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="RP" casNumber="000115-86-6" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="1e11ae72-917e-57e2-98e5-db021c65f2f3" productionVolumeAmount="25000000.0" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">triphenyl phosphate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Triphenyl phosphate production is the result of the reaction of phosphorus oxychloride and phenol. The final product is usually either in flakes or in liquid form, it is transported in jacketed vessel ensuring continuous heating (Brooke et al. 2009).The global production volume in 2000 of triphenyl phosphate was estimated to be between 20 and 30 thousand tonnes; the entire production was supplied by 15 companies (OECD 2002). 90% of this product is used as a flame retardant for different products: 50% for PVC production; 22% polymers (non PVC); 11% printed circuit boards; 7% photographic films (OECD 2002).

Reference(s):
Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de
Brooke, D. N. et al. 2009. Using science to create a better place: Environmental risk evaluation report: Triphenyl phosphate (CAS no. 115-86-6). Environment Agency
OECD. 2002. SIDS Initial Assessment Report For SIAM 15. TRIPHENYL PHOSPHATE CAS N°: 115-86-6. UNEP PUBLICATIONS
</comment>
